
Common False Positives AND Clarifications!

🔥 1) Common False Positives — Pass‑the‑Hash (PtH)
PtH is noisy because NTLM is still used legitimately in many environments.

✅ Common false positives:
Legacy systems (old servers, old apps) that still use NTLM

Print servers (NTLM authentication is extremely common)

File shares accessed by many users

VPN appliances that authenticate using NTLM

Jump servers where many admins authenticate from the same host

Backup servers that authenticate to many machines

Monitoring tools (SolarWinds, SCCM, Lansweeper, etc.)

Service accounts that authenticate across multiple hosts

Why these cause false positives
Because PtH detection relies on:

NTLM - PtH uses NTLM challenge‑response
LogonType 3 - Remote authentication (SMB, WMI, WinRM, PsExec) uses LogonType 3 (Lateral movement almost always uses LogonType 3)
Multiple hosts or unusual hosts
But many legitimate systems behave exactly like that.




🔥 2) Common False Positives — Pass‑the‑Ticket (PtT)
PtT is trickier because Kerberos is everywhere.

Common false positives:
Load balancers (multiple hosts using the same service account)

Clustered servers (failover nodes share tickets)

Citrix / RDS farms (same user logs in from many hosts)

Service accounts running on multiple servers

Kerberos delegation scenarios

Kerberos renewals that look like reused tickets

Misconfigured SPNs causing weird ticket behavior

Why these cause false positives
Because PtT detection often looks for:

Same ticket used from multiple hosts

Kerberos logons without AS‑REQ

LogonType 9 (NewCredentials)

But legitimate enterprise systems do this all the time.



🔥 3) For PtT — does it have to be different IPs? No.

A Pass‑the‑Ticket attack can absolutely happen from one IP.

Why?
Because the attacker may:

Already be on the compromised host

Inject the stolen ticket into LSASS on the same machine

Use the forged ticket locally to escalate privileges

When PtT does involve multiple IPs:
When the attacker steals a ticket from Host A

And reuses it on Host B

That’s the classic detection pattern.

But single‑host PtT is still valid:
Especially when the attacker is escalating locally

Or pivoting to domain admin on the same machine

So yes — one IP can still be an attack.


🔥 4) DCSync — how can a non‑DC account perform DC operations?
This is one of the most misunderstood attacks.

A non‑DC account can perform DCSync if it has these rights:
Replicating Directory Changes

Replicating Directory Changes All

Replicating Directory Changes In Filtered Set


These rights allow the account to request:

Password hashes

Kerberos keys

NTLM hashes

All AD secrets


How attackers get these rights:

Compromise a domain admin

Compromise an account with delegated replication rights

Modify ACLs on the domain root

Abuse misconfigurations (common in old AD environments)



Why it works
DCSync uses the Directory Replication Service Remote Protocol (DRSR).
Any account with replication rights can impersonate a DC.

This is by design — not a bug.


🔥 5) Why do we exclude machine accounts?
Machine accounts end with $.

Reasons to exclude them:
1) They authenticate constantly
Servers and workstations authenticate:

To DCs
To each other
To services
To file shares

This creates massive noise.

2) Machine accounts use NTLM and Kerberos frequently
This would drown your detections in false positives.

3) Machine accounts often have legitimate replication rights
Especially:

Exchange servers
ADFS servers
SCCM servers
Domain controllers



4) Attackers rarely use machine accounts for credential theft
They want user accounts, especially privileged ones.

So excluding machine accounts is a noise‑reduction strategy, not a security assumption.



How can a non‑DC account legitimately have DCSync rights?
This is one of the most misunderstood parts of AD security.

These rights are not exclusive to domain controllers.
Any account can be granted:

Replicating Directory Changes
Replicating Directory Changes All
Replicating Directory Changes In Filtered Set


Who legitimately gets these rights?
✔ Exchange servers
Exchange needs to read directory data, including password hashes for mailbox migrations.

✔ ADFS servers
They need replication rights for token signing and validation.

✔ SCCM / MECM servers
They often get replication rights for user discovery.

✔ Backup solutions
Veeam, Commvault, Rubrik — many require replication rights.

✔ Identity sync tools
Azure AD Connect (ADSync) has these rights by design.

✔ Misconfigurations
Admins sometimes accidentally grant these rights to:

Helpdesk groups
Service accounts
Application accounts
Custom admin roles


So yes — user accounts, service accounts, and admin accounts can all have replication rights.
And attackers love this because:

They don’t need domain admin
They just need an account with replication rights
Then they can DCSync and dump the entire domain



🔥 3) Why don’t attackers use machine accounts? They can be privileged too, right?
Machine accounts can be privileged — but attackers avoid them for several reasons:

1) Machine accounts rotate passwords automatically
Every 30 days by default.

This makes persistence harder.

2) Machine accounts authenticate constantly
They generate:
Kerberos
NTLM
LDAP
SMB
RPC

This creates massive noise and makes attacker activity harder to hide.

3) Machine accounts rarely have interactive logons
Attackers want:

RDP
PowerShell
WMI
WinRM
SMB lateral movement

Machine accounts don’t support these well.


4) Machine accounts rarely have replication rights
Except:

Domain controllers
Exchange servers
ADFS servers


5) User accounts give attackers more flexibility
They can escalate

They can blend in
They can move laterally
They can access cloud resources
Machine accounts are limited.


















